The Chronicle Sikhumbuzo Moyo, Senior Reporter
A 54-YEAR-OLD man from Umguza district in Matabeleland North province last week axed his wife to death and blamed evil spirits for influencing him.  Sikhanyisiwe Zondo of Mawayilesini Village in Insuza locked the bedroom hut before fleeing the scene. His wifeâ€™s lifeless body was discovered by their 13-year-old daughter. Police arrested Zondo on June 14, the same day he axed his wife, Ms Nothando Mnkandla, (49) while she was asleep. <img class="wp-image-615195 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-31-2.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-31-2.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-31-2-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Inspector Glory Banda According to Matabeleland North provincial spokesperson Inspector Glory Banda, when Zondo was arrested, he was found with a class one snare wire which he said he intended to use to commit suicide. He was also found with a written note blaming evil spirits for influencing him to commit murder. There has been a sharp increase in domestic violence cases which in some cases has resulted in death since the outbreak of the Covid-19 pandemic in 2020. <img class="alignnone wp-image-620803 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-53-11.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-53-11.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-53-11-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The Zimbabwe Gender Commission said domestic violence cases increased by more than 100 percent since the outbreak of the pandemic.